The menu of an obese child: he does not have breakfast and eats for dinner sausage
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Current surveys have shown - obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of the overweight children had potatoes for the evening meal on the day before the educational campaign under the motto "Adiposity is not a coincidence".
In families with dicks, sport is not exactly one of the favorite occupations, but it also affects the majority of today's students - only 15 percent answered that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place at the end of the school year last year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second year of the campaign "Adiposity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Fund and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of movement in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the appallingly increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed, for example, reported eating breakfast-second breakfast-lunch-vesper-dinner-in-mode five times a day – one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” according to one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative trifles, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are important for a child’s healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the pupils’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
Worst of all was the finding that in every tenth family no breakfast is served at all.
Breakfast is the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey showed that in families of overweight children, unhealthy potatoes are consumed much more often.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed play sports, only less than half of their parents do — only 15 percent.
Set up your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compile their own meal plan according to appetite and opinion.
"What Czech children between 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and of course sweet dishes.
"Alarming is above all the great popularity of sweet lemonades," the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, pasta won just before poultry.
The children almost did not like legumes and also the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Approach to health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"In the control group of the survey participants, who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the enlightening lecture "Adiposity is not a coincidence", in many cases there was a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy diet, "is stated in the results of the project.
This was obvious, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
The children also crossed in the questionnaire much more often poultry or fish as the main course of the day and were ready to eat less dumplings or sweet foods.
