V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Reviewed
The initially carefree ride is caused by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant errors in the routine ride to the early stage.
We managed to fulfill the ambitions for the most part, but what good is that if obviously no one had the desire to do a little more?
Even before he got to the store tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" raised high expectations.
After all, he promised to move the already-aged game series "Need for Speed" again to a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he did not actually seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious as to how the fitted passages turn out, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to with NFS, in the end, much is different than you expected.
Sure - potentially they are quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is fraught with some superfluous flaws that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they’re not really mistakes anymore, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time, they are introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal character; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, that is, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
One does not have the impression that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
Nothing that moves the world.
But the drive through the desert, through autumn landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Occasionally, atypical elements bring a little variation to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm, which severely restricts the view.
In the mountains, in turn, you have to be careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well in succession.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overcome the required number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to pick up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police are also involved in this, which wants to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages in which Jack leaves the car.
This is more about certain interactive animations in which Jack escapes from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (only three in particular).
Ultimately, this is the thing rather to the advantage, because so this element has at least no chance of getting bored - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model steps in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today's point of view, although it does not tear down trees, on the other hand, one could not say that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you need to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed racing will still be well suited to the local driving model, although you could find better ones in the competition.
Until then, everything is in good order.
Real problems do not appear until after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not entirely OK.
From a game of this kind is hardly expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have practically no idea before any impact on any object, how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: In the case of close overtaking or passing on opposite cars, in some places you "strike" the other car only slightly, but in other, almost identical situations you get into the throttle and turn wild pirouettes.
Or the car will go to waste.
Thanks to the restart system, it does not matter any more, it is always annoying.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far off the track, then the game throws you back to the last point of the track.
Only - in each race you have only five restarts.
When you have exhausted them, everything starts from the front..
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you should not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, not even the restart helps, since nothing helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
It’s very unfortunate that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, you have to go through some curves in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
Elsewhere you will encounter "civil" cars in the same configuration, whether you arrive first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see the opponent pass two cars in front of you, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to circumnavigate them or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, everything is designed in such a way that it always comes close to your nose.
The contractors have other advantages.
Throughout the game, there are a few places where you are always overtaken by the same opponent at the same place and also here again regardless of the time.
The craziest is this to finish the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent has to obviously overtake one of the devils out here.
And if he is already in front of you, then of course he takes the view, so that you drive your own car a few times in lump.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly disappears the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite the simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and sometimes also so loaded with action that you almost don’t know where one’s head is.
And in principle, it does not matter what is "guilty" of it - the concept with fifty unique routes, the arrangement of the races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the change of car during the races.
You should not miss the gas stations on the route, because here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you just have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American sedans for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the mode of the game story also goes the task mode (challenges) - that is, the races in the individual localities that you know from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and history.
To get to the higher level of the driver, different items must be unlocked: from the car to the backgrounds for the profile.
This is simultaneously connected to the online function Autolog, which among other things compares the own results achieved with those of other players and also provides for other collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (because of me), where you can rest in the dark on the rails for a long time (because of me).
On the tacho, numbers look between 150 and 200 km/h (due to me), but suddenly a subway comes from behind and drives uncompromisingly to scrap.
In our editorial we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think us so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is quite appealing in most cases and here and there even brilliant.
The more annoying it is, that in some exciting moments the image recovery frequency slows down and this is sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this is especially true for accidents with a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use to you anyway.
The sound is OK and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to reach as wide a scale as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack a l<0xC3><0xA1> "something" was created - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
If the game hadn’t been narrowed down by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary flaws, we would have been able to assert with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But somehow the game seems unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared to face these mistakes with the power of airport headlights.
