Brand Story:
Innovator IBM enters the second century of its existence
If you wanted to look for a suitable word that most accurately characterizes IBM’s strategy, it would probably be the word “longevity”.
For the general public, IBM is synonymous with technological revolution, it is known as a modern company, although it has passed a century since its foundation.
The basis for this longevity was already laid by her first boss - the visionary Thomas J. Watson sen.
Already he represented the slogan, countless worldwide problems could easily be solved if people were willing to think a little.
His slogan "Think!" became a trademark for the life of the future giant (and at the same time the title of the company's in-house magazine, which began to be published at IBM as early as 1935).
This was also the basis of the corporate culture thoroughly prepared by Watsen.
“For us at IBM, this long-term thinking means a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and was successful for a century because it remained true to its principles and did not shy away from changing everything else around.
This allowed us, over the course of our first century, to transform the technologies, the business and also the society.
We hope to do even more in the next hundred years,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current CEO on the occasion of the anniversary.
A well-thought-out system
Watson was already in the thirties in the social care of his employees - in a similar way to the entrepreneur Bata in Czechoslovakia: the IBM people had paid holidays as one of the first American employees, an insurance by the entrepreneur plus elegant uniforms as work clothes and a well-thought-out salary system.
IBM’s long-term relationships with its customers are equally sophisticated.
The company was brilliant in talent promotion from the beginning - as one of the first companies in the world, IBM lifted any discrimination - and was able to choose accordingly.
In line with this anti-discrimination strategy is also the current plan to replace Palmisan at the top of IBM next year by a woman – Virginia Rometty.
She has been with IBM for thirty years, so far she has taken the position of Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
IBM has been doing so-called online brainstorming in recent years, from which many future strategies and innovations emerge.
No wonder - there are enough ideas, almost half a million people are employed in the company.
An institution with a good reputation
Its unwavering position in the business guarantees the company a strong image, both internally and externally.
“From the outset, IBM had the concept of an institution rather than a mere technology company,” said Harvard Business School professor and author of a book about IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that helps solve business problems using technology,” added George Colony of consulting firm Forrester Research.
As the company itself emphasizes, it is a difference to be only present in the market or to shape it directly through this presence.
IBM - in the states of its logo because of the familiar "Big Blue", has grown into one of the largest companies in the world in a century.
It is one of the most versatile technology companies ever - IBM develops hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting services in an incredible range of products - from servers to nanotechnology.
Of all American technology companies, IBM holds the most patents, and five of its employees have already been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His most well-known inventions include, for example, ATMs, credit cards, financial swaps, barcodes or even the floppy disks.
With approximately $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM was the second-largest technology company this year (just like Apple), surpassing Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
The foreseeable future
Not all products and innovations met the taste of today's customers - unhappy were, for example, the attempt with its own operating system OS/2, the online service Prodigy or even the computers IBM PC Jr.
“Business is based on the forward movement, so you can’t be emotionally tied to the past,” says Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its foundations on different platforms – and if they don’t work, leaving them too.
In contrast to the opponent Microsoft, which in principle stands and falls with its operating system Windows.
Promising technologies
IBM’s revenues are largely driven by services, software and hardware, accounting for one-fifth of each.
In 1990, hardware with a share of more than fifty percent was the most represented.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion in low-profit assets, while at the same time it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future-proof technologies.
These investments continue even after 2008, when the modern financial crisis swept the world for the first time like a storm.
Here, too, IBM remained faithful to the legacy of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who increased its investment amid the great global economic crisis.
So far, it seems that the company IBM survives the current crisis unharmed.
The value of IBM shares has increased by 120 percent in a rocket-like manner since 2008, and the company’s net profit is growing continuously.
IBM’s corporate slogan is: Everything can be changed – only the values cannot be changed.
This is also why it can be expected that this flexible giant will also cope with the next crisis.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
Founded a hundred years ago in New York, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924 - originally it was a brand name for an office in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the later IBM company was the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They possessed technologies such as the famous punch-card clocks for registering the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired Thomas J. Watson, the head of the competition company, to help him run the company.
This leader even overshadowed IBM’s founders – based on Watson’s ideas to this day, the company’s invincible culture and identity.
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began manufacturing and distributing all sorts of machines for trade – from sausage and cheese slicers to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to nine million dollars and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, engineers and computers from IBM helped NASA direct flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous flight of man to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of the time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant share of PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus fully entered the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the “Smarter Planet” concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not even planned so far, e.g. also to improve the situation in transport and urban management.
In the trading sector, IBM recently introduced the "Smart Commerce" platform, which is designed to help traders lead the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
In 1932, IBM established a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central Office for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague and here is also a top-level research team that deals with the technology of voice recognition.
