Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five authorized state travel agencies in the then <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time mainly sold only trips to the socialist eastern bloc countries, in the west only select people were allowed at that time.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic Sea (to the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Sochi on the peninsula of Crimea on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (also the Czechoslovaks) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then, the travel agencies also offered trips to the west, but then you had to buy huge snakes or also spend the night in a sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
This was not the case for a long time.
The so-called currency usage - the condition for a trip to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without currency use it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs therefore spent their holidays in the country, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and Datschen - a habit that continues to this day.
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs on foot.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox, of which one is no longer aware, is the fact that one could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, the foreign exchange obligation was lifted in the neighboring Western European countries, which resulted in a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to be there for at least a few days.
For example, the Czech holidaymakers slept in a tent in the park when traveling to Paris, because who would have had the money for accommodation in a hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of travel abroad from the Czech Republic at that time was a packed trunk with cans, beer and sausage, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our standard of living, and thus the average wages, rose, which led to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to prepare for charter flights on a regular basis, which made air travel incredibly cheap compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of negotiating volume discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already had currency-free payment transactions with all the advanced countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-all" tourism came in 2000, when thanks to high demand, the first direct charter flight to an exotic country was made - to Thailand.
Since then, Czech direct charter planes with Czech passengers have been flying to far-flung sunny countries every year; this year, twelve exotic destinations are flying directly from the Czech Republic.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel annually to exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our “post-revolutionary” development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent for the first time more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history they spent more than CZK 15 Tsd. per capita for a single holiday.
