Jump Into The Blue
by Julia Stanek
Ufo-style paddling pools, pruning pools in Budapest: those who travel through Europe can experience its blue wonder - and after a city tour or hike, the tired legs rest in squirrel baths.
A book shows where well-being in the water is most beautiful.
When Iris Meder went on a research trip in the past one and a half years, one thing in her luggage was not to be missed: her swimsuit.
Leaning back on the water, she looked up into artfully designed domes, swam towards marble pits waiting for her at the edge of the basin, and marveled at meticulously restored Art Nouveau swimming halls.
Liked a bath, she took it up in her notebook - along with knowledgeable details about the construction and history of the building.
More than 200 swimming pools explored architectural historian Meder in this way - and now introduces her in her recently published book "Badefreuden": Volksschwimmhallen in Munich, historic bathing palaces in the Black Forest, "Hardcore concrete buildings" in the Taunus.
Through 13 countries, she led her "trip to the most extraordinary baths in Central Europe": in addition to Germany, Austria and Switzerland, she visited places in Italy, France, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Slovenia, Hungary, Romania, Poland - and in each case a city in Luxembourg, Serbia and Croatia.
The 46-year-old German is a true bathing culture enthusiast.
With sport, she doesn't have much to worry about, says Meder - only in the water is different.
Only annoying that swimmers have to settle for blue tiles and chlorine tank, while joggers can breathe in the alluring scent of spruce forests or listen to the cheerful bird whistle in the park.
“One day I wondered why swimming pools have to be so ugly,” says the Meder, who lives in Vienna.
"So I started collecting nice baths."
Water surface doubles the architecture
Slabs in the jumping pool and essential sauna oils - the wellness factor in bathrooms is so great because all the senses are served, according to Meder.
And when the builders have worked hard, swimming halls can be a real eye-catcher: "Instead of a floor, you have a water surface in bathrooms."
"On the one hand, it is transparent, but on the other hand, it reflects the beauty of the whole building."
Everything doubles optically: high vaults, colorful tiles, jumping boards.
The small-format picture book "Badefreuden" conveys on 190 pages valuable information about the architectural and cultural history of historical wellness oases - but above all it makes you want to jump into the blue.
Remarkable specimens were discovered by the pool collector Meder during her research in Hungary.
In addition to magnificent healing baths such as the 100-year-old Széchenyi Bath in Budapest, she found a nitrate-containing water in a quaint karst cave (cave bath in Miskolc-Tapolca) as well as a thermal bath, whose basins are filled with alkali-containing water and are located in a bottle-shaped building in J<0xC3><0xA1>rmosy<0xC3><0xA1>l.
Spectacular views, on the other hand, offer many heated outdoor swimming pools in Switzerland and Austria: while you have the whole city in mind from the Zurich rooftop swimming pool, you can look at the snow-covered Arlberg in the outdoor swimming pool in St. Anton - and: In the steam bath there is a window from which you can watch the operation on the ski slopes.
Perhaps the most extraordinary pool design awaits bathers in Längenfeld: The Aquadome <0xC3><0x96>tztal looks like a UFO just landed in the Alps.
From three open bowls it evaporates in winter, while in the background the mountains of the <0xC3><0x96>tztal rise into the sky.
Alhambra in the Black Forest
Not in every swimming pool did the pool collector Meder smell the smell of chlorine in her nose.
Many thermal baths smell of sulphur, in the <0xC3><0x81>rp<0xC3><0xA1>d bath in Békescsaba, Hungary, it smells so strongly of heating oil that it is hardly believed to have landed in a health bath.
The smell comes from the alkaline-hydrogen carbonate-containing healing water, which is almost black and the slick of which sticks to one's skin as soon as one glides into the pelvis - a wellness experience of a special kind.
In one place, however, Iris Meder was also disappointed in her search for beautiful bathing spots: when she wanted to visit the outdoor and sunbathing in the Czech bath Luhatschowitz, she found a locked plot of land.
The bathroom, designed by architect Du<0xC5><0xA1>an Jurkovic in 1902, has now been closed.
As Meder glanced through the weathered windows of the red-white-yellow Art Nouveau building, she saw weeds grow between the tiles.
Counteracting the decay, on the other hand, is a magical swimming pool in the Black Forest: the Palais Thermal in Bad Wildbad.
Three phases of construction have already taken place; you can discover not only neo-Romanesque elements dating from the time of its construction in 1844, but also a Moorish hall in the Alhambra style, which was added around 1900.
Since its careful modernization in 1995, the Palais Thermal has been the favorite bath of pool connoisseur Iris Meder - and not only because it originally comes from the Black Forest.
“It’s already an achievement to merge such different building styles into such a great unit,” says Meder.
In such a palace, diving in the thermal pool is apparently only a side effect.
