21st house in Vienna
The relocated pavilion
Von Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with heights, depths and happy end: The Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion in Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and empty.
Now it is reopened as an exhibition house.
When warmed by modern post-war architecture, clear forms, glass halls, bold swings and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer is a striking and famous example for the Brussels World Exhibition in 1958.
Schwanzer’s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d’Architecture for its lightweight and floating steel-glass construction.
The building is still considered to be a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built Austria’s pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like side-construction in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
Its pavilion, planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the World Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the Vienna South Railway Station, rebuilt and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened in it - the "20th house" was called it.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art got a new home in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building was empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has remodeled the pavilion, it is now called "21er Haus" and will be used as a museum for contemporary art in the future.
On Tuesday evening, the Museum Belvedere, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition - a lucky one in every respect.
Agnes Husslein-Arco is the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere.
Husslein-Arco, a doctoral art historian with considerable careers, among others in her youth as an ice-artist runner, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, carried out the conversion with great intensity among politicians and protectors of monuments, and publicly procured funds from them.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the eponymous foundation, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office house had to be built for it.
Strict supervision, small state
Krischanitz was then the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded Joseph Olbrich’s Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion was for him an “extremely important place” where he had watched the exhibitions “almost every weekend”.
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which had already lost its generosity and lightness when it was moved to Vienna and reused.
There were far bigger problems with the current renovation: the building was "an energy sling", says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, glass fiber reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been refurbished.
Two basements provided space for new use, a lowered trench between house and road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection hue.
The cinema is exactly the same as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small state.
"Often had to be found a material that is good and cheap and also liked the monument protection office," says Krischanitz, pointing to a rugged floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and renovations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the pavilion that “came from Brussels,” Krishanitz recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city story.”
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "raise a real awareness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because an urban accident has occurred: around the Swiss garden, the completely newly planned "Hauptbahnhofsquartier", with office and residential buildings, is being created.
And another case of luck may occur: the 21st house could be reinforced by another Krishanitz building, because the collector Francesca of Habsburg has bought the Berlin Temporary Art Hall, and as you hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss garden.
