The Scandal Bank of Lake Zurich
The most adventurous bank in Europe is not in Italy or France, but in Switzerland.
UBS almost went bankrupt in the financial crisis and has since climbed from one crisis to the next.
Now let a German judge.
Axel Weber certainly didn’t think so.
After his spectacular departure from the top of the Bundesbank, it was announced in July that he would be taking on an almost equally spectacular new job in 2013: Chairman of the Board of Directors of the Swiss Großbank UBS - an unexpected and lucrative career step.
Axel Weber rejoiced publicly, praised Switzerland for its beauty and UBS for its newly acquired solidity and dropped friendly remarks about future colleagues.
"The UBS has made the turnaround".
"I look forward to working with Kaspar Villiger and Oswald Grübel".
But in September, it became clear that everything was going to be different.
A UBS dealer in London had bypassed all of the bank’s hedging systems and squandered around 1.7 billion euros.
UBS CEO Oswald Grübel, a banker not only famous in Switzerland, had to leave.
Since then, the chairman of the board of directors of UBS has also been considered a hit – and everyone is asking: When will Axel Weber finally arrive?
It has already been announced that Weber will be allowed to advise the bank from February 2012.
And he will take over the chairmanship of the Board of Directors as early as May - not until 2013, as the bank announced on Tuesday.
This is going to be tough for Axel Weber.
He is not a banker, but rather a professor of economics and a central banker, and would certainly have needed a period of processing.
With a stroke, he then takes responsibility for the strategy of a bank, which has just proven once again that it has long earned the title of "biggest scandal bank in Europe".
Because UBS is huge on the one hand - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other hand it has been climbing from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, remains the once so proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007, UBS had an excellent reputation.
The image of the hidden and solid, but also sophisticated Swiss asset manager had combined her with ambitious goals: she also wanted to become a very large number in investment banking.
In 2007, UBS managed $1.6 trillion more cash-rich customers than any other bank in the world.
And on the other hand, as an investment bank, it was ahead of the league of the world’s largest banks.
That made an impression.
Hans Geiger, a former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich, says: “I always set the UBS as a model for my students at that time.”
“From today’s perspective, you ask yourself, ‘How could I be so wrong?’
He made a big mistake.
In 2007, it became apparent for the first time that something really went wrong at UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli surprisingly resigned, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker.
A few months later, he knew why he had left.
The bank’s investment stake had been cluttered with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To shoulder this, UBS announced a capital increase in the amount of CHF 13 billion.
In fact, she found investors, but some of them, some of whom until recently would have nodded their heads: an opaque Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund that was so silent that one did not even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
It got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new billions in losses, with Marcel Ospel, chairman of the board of directors, still the second best-paid board of directors in Switzerland, resigning in 2006.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: UBS faced the collapse and had to be rescued by the state in the face of its misinvestments in the financial crisis.
The National Bank bought out UBS for tens of billions of troubled securities, while the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced convertible bond, through which it could become a co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - because it noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it hosts such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS 2007 was more than five times the economic performance of Switzerland (see graph).
“Once again, we could not save UBS,” says bank researcher Geiger.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
A few months later, UBS capitulated in a tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have been taxed with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a payment of $780 million - as a repayment of unjustified profits from these transactions, including a penalty charge.
As a result, UBS was more or less open to helping with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for rich customers: the nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, the Swiss banking secrecy was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of the Chairman of the Board of Directors and the Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both core business areas: in investment banking through mis speculation and in asset management through tax evasion assistance.
And just as it got a little quieter again, just as you thought UBS would get it back, here’s this nasty trader story: A single trader squandered 1.7 billion euros before the bank noticed that something was going wrong.
And it becomes obvious: with risk management in investment banking, it obviously still does not work.
"With the Adoboli case, one has to find that risk control has changed too little," says Martin Janssen, economist and professor of finance at the Bank Institute of the University of Zurich.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also sure: "The problem with UBS is that it does not have control over risk."
It was precisely the idea of the caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago set out to become guardians of the great wealth of the world: not too great a risk, security for money - even beyond the Alpine Republic the world might once collapse.
The safes of the Swiss banks had become a symbol of unwavering reliability such as Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly noble chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the well-developed Swiss private bank - it is only a little larger.
The situation is already classic.
The bank is headquartered on Zurich’s Bahnhofstraße, which leads directly from the main station to Lake Zurich, which is framed by the snow-capped peaks of the Swiss mountains.
The buildings here are splendid, the store rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewellery such as Tiffany's can be found here among Swiss traditional shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
Swiss banks have resided here for centuries: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Bär.
You enter the reception hall of the UBS through a heavy turning door.
Inside, the walls are decorated with marble, in front of which there are thick leather armchairs, next to the bank logo a large sign for the "safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has been repressed by both Swiss major banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point – or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he does business with the two big banks.
The UBS has become much too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons had also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if so, they have long adapted to the customs of the angelic axes."
In fact, it was Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, first gave it high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the Subprime jungle as the Swiss Grand Bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"That Wednesday, the government coalition of the small country of seven million decided the largest rescue operation in the history of their nation," author Lukas Hässig writes in his book "The UBS crash".
Up to 68 billion francs, or around 45 billion euros, the politicians granted to save the big bank facing bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem especially in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three major Swiss banks merged into a large group.
A bank was created, which was already too big for the small Switzerland at the time of the merger - and it kept growing.
The two different predecessor banks of UBS helped to complement each other: a rich but sleepy bank with a focus on asset management in Zurich and a poorer but already more internationalized one.
All of a sudden, the internationalized investment bankers came up with a lot of money, with which they could spin a huge wheel.
Two names are associated with this rise of UBS: Peter Wuffli, CEO of UBS from 2001 to 2007, and Marcel Ospel, then Chairman of the Board of Directors.
“I always thought Wuffli and Ospel were a dream team,” says bank researcher Hans Geiger.
"Wuffli, the highly intellectual, modest, who understands a lot of models and statistics, and Ospel, the belly man who has worked up from banking to the top."
But Ospel ultimately relied on Wuffli.
And Wuffli probably made a crucial mistake in the end: "He thought his models were the reality," says Geiger.
“This is a tragic case.”
Tragic, maybe.
It is clear that pride came before the fall.
Employees of UBS clearly remember the executive meetings at which CEO Wuffli repeatedly issued the same slogan: Goldman Sachs is knocking off the throne.
The American Bank was the most powerful investment bank in the world.
She led the "League Tables", the rankings that documented the success of the banks of that time.
That's where the UBS wanted to go, all the way up.
She had already taken a few steps.
In the foreign exchange business and in the stock trading, she played at the top.
However, company consultants who were commissioned highlighted a weakness: in the international interest rate business, in the banking language "Fixed Income", there is a huge distance to the largest banks.
UBS has gaps in U.S. mortgage products.
To close this gap, UBS embarked on an adventure that almost cost them their lives.
Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a pre-founded hedge fund invested in American subprime investments.
It developed into a huge machine that packaged and distributed securities on American mortgage loans – but also kept risks.
Even when other banks have long been looking for the exit.
“Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was in flames, UBS bought there,” says banking expert Geiger.
So great the euphoria, so deep the case.
One manager after another had to go, as attempts to clean up turned out to be more difficult than expected.
Posts at UBS have become the headquarter of Schleuderer and are still volatile.
Whoever runs the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He has to find a strategy for a bank that has missed all the obvious business models.
Banking researcher Geiger already has an idea: Stop investment banking, focus on asset management, return to Swiss roots.
The bank does not (yet) want to go that far.
But investment banking is supposed to shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
On Thursday, the new bank manager Sergio Ermotti wants to present his future strategy to the world.
The 51-year-old Italo-Swiss was actually only intended as a transitional solution when the bank surprisingly separated from its predecessor, Grübel.
In the meantime, he has asserted that he is to conduct the business of UBS permanently, the Zurich Bank announced on Tuesday.
Ermotti wants the investment bank to go back to the mid-1990s.
He has 3,500 jobs.
But that will not suffice.
UBS needs a vision.
Who is she?
What does she want to make money from?
These are the questions that Axel Weber is probably asking himself right now.
So far, he has only said publicly that he and his wife will be looking for an apartment in Zurich.
Next year.
