Smart crows are spreading in cities
In many places, seed crows are considered "problem birds": But from the cities, the highly intelligent animals can no longer be driven, experts claim.
Some people like them, others want to get rid of them very quickly: crows have been part of the cityscape for centuries, but in many municipalities, residents complain about the dirt and noise of the animals.
A remedy against the "problem birds" is not yet in sight.
Seed crows are no longer to be obtained from the cities, experts said at the first crow symposium in the East Frisian void.
There, experts from all over the federal territory consulted on possible solutions.
You are looking for alternatives in the cities
Conservationists also attributed the problems in cities to the exodus of specially protected seed crows: the use of chemicals in agriculture is increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
The hunting, increasing settlement and the fall of typical brood trees made life difficult for the birds.
Crows are protected by nature.
There are large colonies with more than 600 breeding pairs in the Westphalian Soest, in the north-west, among others in Jever, Diepholz and Achim near Bremen, as well as in Leer.
There, in 2005, a controversial project for the mass killing of crows in the county provided negative headlines.
Critics had described the capture of the animals in bird traps and the killing with knuckles as particularly brutal.
"The normal expulsion, the embezzlement, brings nothing," said the city and landscape planner Werner Klöver.
Spraying nests with water or falling trees often have undesirable consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Kaiser from Lahr in Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals diverge, large colonies split up and spread elsewhere."
Harassment is only conceivable as an exception to hospitals, nursing homes or schools.
“We have to live with them, we can’t get them away.”
Without the surrounding area, the problem cannot be solved in the cities, said the mayor Wolfgang Kellner from empty.
A combination of germination of the animals from sensitive living areas and lock offers to resettle them in other places is conceivable.
The psychologist and ethnologist Uta Maria Jürgens, on the other hand, advocated for a completely different treatment of the animals: "One pimple in the face we can finally tolerate with confidence."
In Schleswig-Holstein, Jürgens had co-founded the Ascheberger Krähen-Lehrpfad, where signs inform about the lives of highly intelligent seed crows.
The project is already being accepted by tourists.
Jürgens also had his own opinion on the criticism of the noise of birds: "There is a lot of communication, they have a lot to say."
The intelligence and skill of the animals are legendary: seed crows not only use tools to get to a treat, but even make their own tools as tools.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested four seed crows on how far the birds’ intelligence reaches.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they must use stones to bring a scaffold to collapse in order to reach a moth larva.
Without much training, they purposefully recognized what size and shape a stone must have in order for the platform to collapse.
In a second attempt, the clever crows then had to solve a more tricky problem.
In a vertical cylinder, the researchers had placed a small bucket with a moth larva.
With the beak the birds could not reach their prey.
However, the researchers had laid wire pieces on them.
From this all four animals formed a hook, with the help of which they then fished the bucket on the handle from the tube.
Three of the four seed crows even managed to do this at once.
