Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed an amok run in Norway in July, killing 77 people, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is far from alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time before his attack on his computer and chatted with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing extremist groups on social networking sites.
After the tragedy this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It’s easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found that it wasn’t hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report by the UK’s DEMOS Ideas Factory on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately pinpoint their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then targeted them with Adds, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey that asked them about their educational status, their attitude to violence, and their assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without having to leave their office even once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online promoters of right-wing extremist groups are usually young, male, and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers, and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as likes, text messages, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific papers titled this page by nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that you can study through this site people you don’t usually reach with your clipboard on the street.
"When you tried to interview people of the British National Party in the past, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have granted them access,” Bartlett said.
“With Facebook, it all falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues has found that students who discussed their full-blown rage on Facebook are significantly more likely to have problem drinking than students who remain silent on this topic.
Moreno suggests that peers, such as housing counselors, monitor the site and help a student post too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you haven’t realized it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Moreno’s co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
"We have found a way to identify at-risk children who would not otherwise have been found."
Facebook also constantly taps the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to – Masters of Digital Freedom have long known that the site should make its vast data mine accessible to others for research purposes.)
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. In order to be able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to release your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about yet?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles at all,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he surveyed the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she's concerned, it's just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a researcher is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information in a user profile and in posts is true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There’s no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research needs to take care of social – and lots of social life is still taking place offline.”
