7 Lessons from the Interview with the Deceased Steve Jobs Shown This Week in a Theater
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the genius of technology as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently rediscovered job interview, which was dusted off this week before special film screenings in the major markets, is how much this creative head has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer and a self-appointed hippie, but he was also an meticulous organizer who eagerly crafted diagrams - a man who believed that many CEOs suffer from "a disease of thinking," "that a really great idea makes up 90 percent of the work... [but] there's an enormous amount of work going on."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Professional Idiots" about the break-up of the personal computer. And he sat together for more than an hour with jobs, in which they conducted one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By that time, it had been 10 years since Jobs had been forced from Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, and was looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley’s interview was used in specialist idiots, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing at the time of delivery.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a complete VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which arrives at the Landmark Theater this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known for abhorring detailed interviews, Jobs here appears surprisingly zealous in explaining his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
In the course of the interview, there are four times longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts and strives for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seems impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and urges him to deal more quickly with topics or side actions of greater importance.
Before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone recorded, the Lost Interview appears somehow eeriely far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies do right or wrong in his opinion and represents his own vision for the future of the computer.
