Ninety days later we had a mouse that we could build for $15. That was incredibly credible.
About big companies that are slowing down:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs foresaw the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled with their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Say, you work at IBM or Xerox, so do you make a better copier or printer, then and?"
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [they are] the people who ultimately lead the companies and the product with which people are pushed out of decision making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is eradicated by the people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
This happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
One could have been ten times bigger if it had been the Microsoft of the 1990s...
You have conquered defeat by victory.
Innovation as an art form:
