We also know that when a person has been exposed as an offender, others feel less guilty about having lied to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of this person.
This is called "Baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for the subsequent evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, the laughter, the voice quality of their subject.
You should know better when someone is normally tripling with the foot all the time, so they don’t wrongly accuse him of tripling with the foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and nonverbal behaviors.
Consider these build-ups as alarm bells that scream, not as evidence of detargeting.
