Controversial Oil Pipeline Plan Revisited After Risk of Delayed U.S. Approval
A few days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned oil pipeline from Canada into the Gulf of Mexico, which angered the unions and at the same time reassured environmentalists, the pipeline-building company is trying to re-plan the project so that it can return to normal.
TransCanada said on Monday evening that it will divert the planned pipeline from the ecologically sensitive area of the Sandhills in Nebraska.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Nebraska Parliament Building.
Alex Pourbax of TransCanada said the company remains confident that the pipeline will eventually be approved, albeit with a different course.
This came after an announcement by the Foreign Ministry last week that a decision on a federal approval for the project would be postponed until the new possible course was reviewed, which avoided the area of the Sandhills in Nebraska as well as the Ogallala Aquifer, a large underwater supply.
"This is a real step forward," Republican Lee Terry, a Nebraska Republican, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the foreign ministry may delay a decision until 2013, after the elections next year, even though officials deny that politicians were involved in the decision.
Obama said in a written statement last week that the decision was a matter for the State Department and expressed his support.
The 1700-mile pipeline was connecting Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would pump 700,000 barrels of oil a day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, the pipeline would have to cross six states.
Environmentalists hate them, but labor markets love them, because they estimate that the pipeline creates 20,000 jobs.
But Nebraska’s lawmakers, who are against the plan, are weighing the laws to force a diversion from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala Aquifer, a major source of drinking water and irrigation.
The current study on the environment impact of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs has found that the project would have little impact on the environment, but the energy industry source says that the ministry’s chief inspector has requested a separate probe of the review procedure, which focuses on two issues.
One is whether a lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliott, who was adviser to Hillary Clinton in 2008, is in a conflict of interest.
The other is whether a company commissioned to carry out the original study was an inappropriate choice as it is associated with TransCanada.
