The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet with the President of Italy tomorrow to introduce the new government that is set to face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that the Monti appointed on Sunday would meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, on Wednesday to confirm the formation of the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new prime minister will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the results of the talks with the political parties on the formation of government.
"I would like to reaffirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to cope with these difficult times," the former EU Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly confirm the formation of the government, but his comments show that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well set off," he added.
Monti has managed to form a government in less than three days, which is much less time than usual, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the cost of debt to an unbearable level.
The new government, led by former EU Commissioner Monti, has to pass a tough austerity package that has been demanded by Europoliticians in order to regain the confidence it has gained in Italy.
The pressure to rush Monti has been further intensified by the fluctuating market situation, as a result of which Italian government bonds were charged with 7% interest for 10 years, which corresponds to the situation in which Greece and Ireland were forced to apply for the European bailout umbrella.
Emma Marcegaglia, president of the Italian industrial association Confindustria, told the press after a meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government as much as possible."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency.
Montis’ chances of success were greatly increased by the support of the PDL party by Silvio Berlusconi, who had to step down on Saturday as a result of the crisis.
“We believe that Professor Monti’s efforts are destined to produce good results,” said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is essential because so far many of its members have spoken out against a majority technocratic government that is currently forming Monti.
Support from Parliament
Monti’s new government needs strong parliamentary support to implement the probably unpopular austerity measures.
Resisting his efforts or delaying reforms could once again lead to a devastating attack on the financial markets.
