Peru:
Fujimori returned to the hospital for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a public hospital on Tuesday to examine the muscle loss of his legs, his GP said.
The 72-year-old Fujimori, who served 25 years in prison for human rights violations during his tenure (1990-2000), has several illnesses, including tongue cancer, which he has operated on four times and is under control.
Alejandro Aguinaga, a congressman and his personal doctor, told television that Fujimori would be examined for three days at the Peruvian hospital Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Neoplasicas to determine the cause of his pain and muscle loss in the lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori could be pardoned for humanitarian reasons, but he did not want this because he considered him innocent.
He was operated on four times on tongue cancer and lost 18 kilos of weight, including other diseases such as severe erosive gastritis, a cyst in the pancreas, kidney stones, high blood pressure and blood circulation problems in the legs, the doctor said.
Fujimori has been in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the death squad of the Peruvian army, which was secretly active during his reign.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political relations
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and entrepreneurs, will start their visit from Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and discuss regional political issues.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, which, according to the Uruguayan president, will be the highlight of his booked schedule with politicians, businessmen and a meeting with the collective of Uruguayans living in Mexico.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara "suitable for exchanging information on all policy areas between the two countries," the South American country's presidential office announced on its website.
According to local media, Mujica sought Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n’s support in the incident with France when French Prime Minister Nicolas Sarkozy put the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 summit in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude those countries that still act as tax havens from the international community, which was rejected by Uruguay and prompted a request to his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has chaired the G20 since November, a group of the world's most powerful emerging and industrialized countries. Since January of this year, an agreement has been in place on the exchange of tax information to avoid double taxation with the South American country.
In recent years, the Uruguayan government has tried to speed up the concretization of agreements on the exchange of tax information in order to be removed from the "grey list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), which includes countries that have not adopted all international standards for cooperation in tax matters.
At the business level, a free trade agreement between Mexico and Uruguay has been in place since 2004, which has contributed to a growing exchange of goods between the two countries.
The stringy installer enters the third dimension with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has been fighting tirelessly for the rescue of Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser for 25 years, but so far never in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land", he fights for the love of the girl in stereo technology.
The game, which comes to the counters around the world this month, has been tailored from the beginning to the characteristics of the Ninth 3DS portable console, with which it can be played three-dimensionally without a special glasses.
"Mario is the figure who has to say how stereoscopy works without glasses," said Omar <0xC3><0x81>lvarez, the head of the Nintendo-specialized press in Spain at the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
<0xC3><0x81>lvarez stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" was "the first Nintendo video game to be developed from the start for this console" because hit articles such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" had been adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesperson stressed that, although it is three-dimensional, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "affordable" video game that allows for a fast, fluid game.
<0xC3><0x81>lvarez confirmed that "Super Mario 3D Land" contained two games in one: The first part is "easy" to capture the less skillful users.
After that, the experts can rotate a "second round" over the different levels of play, which are becoming increasingly difficult.
In addition, users can choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action. However, in order to overcome the obstacles without becoming a victim of the "optical effects", it is always necessary to play three-dimensionally.
This trip to the three-dimensional world of Super Mario also means the return of the character to a portable console, which has not been the case since 2005.
With this video game, Nintendo winks at the fans of the saga and repeats the success recipe of the latest editions: the stringy installer has to overcome platforms spiked with dangers to free Princess Peach.
However, the player encounters news about the movements, the environment, the disguises and the enemies - and a "playable" Luigi.
Colom guarantees Portillo's extradition to the United States
Guatemalan President <0xC3><0x81>lvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he would extradite former governor Alfonso Portillo to be held accountable in the United States for the $70 million money laundering conspiracy.
The trial of the U.S. application for the extradition of Portillo ends, so that he can be brought to justice there.
In a press conference, Colom confirmed his decision based on the independence of the judiciary and the government taking into account that a decision-making court had already ordered the extradition.
He stressed that during his administration he had not interfered in court decisions and had accepted all extradition requests that he was notified of.
Apart from Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroqu<0xC3><0xAD>n is extradited for murder and serious bodily injury, Edgar Estrada Morales and V<0xC3><0xAD>ctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
The Coloms procedure is an act of government that takes place when all judicial and constitutional bodies are exhausted to condemn the former president (2000 -2004).
According to the decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court of Guatemala, Portillo must be extradited if his legal situation in Guatemala is clarified and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of undermining 120 million Quetzals in the Ministry of Defense during his reign. This trial preceded the extradition, but the minister filed an objection and revived the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people threatened by social exclusion
The organisation was set up to avoid the marginalization of young people without vocational training.
The first 25 years of life of the social assistance organization Trinijove have led to important results: in this quarter century, 6,000 young people threatened by social exclusion were supported to find a way out of their difficult situation.
In addition, there are more than a hundred jobs created for this social group.
On the occasion of the anniversary, an event in the former factory buildings of Fabra i Coats, in which more than 300 people participated, was held yesterday.
Trinijove was founded in 1986 in the Trinitat Vella district with the aim of helping young people with low levels of education, without work, with drug problems threatened by the risk of marginalization.
Yesterday’s celebration in Sant Andreu was attended by numerous managers of institutions and institutions who have worked with the association in these 25 years.
The participation of political representatives of different directions in election campaigns proved the impartiality of the work carried out by Trinijove.
In addition to the President of the Generalitat (Parliament of the Autonomous Region of Catalonia), Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol attended the celebrations of the former Socialist Minister of Education Ernest Maragall and the former Mayor and currently left-green city councilor Ricard Goma.
The great hall of Fabra i Coats was also visited by the current Catalan Minister of Social Affairs and Family, Josep Llu<0xC3><0xAD>s Cleries, and the Director General of the Social Work of the Savings Bank La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa.
Mas emphasized that Trinijove was born in very difficult times and that today's times are no less complicated, but he added that the work done so far is "a good foundation".
For the president of the Generalitat, Trinijove is an example that knows how to fight difficult circumstances and gives people in difficulty hope.
"The economic crisis is nothing new to the club and the work it does," he said.
Occupied house, where huge parties were held, was cleared
The owners had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments in the building on Balmes Street No. 51 (Barcelona).
The twelve occupants of the house left the building yesterday afternoon without having made any resistance.
Everything indicates that the nightmares of the neighbors of the house No. 51 on Balmes street have come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left the building that they had illegally occupied and where they had organized huge festivities that had driven the neighborhood to despair, and the evacuation was carried out on judicial order without police intervention.
After the evacuation, the door lock was replaced to avoid a similar situation.
"From now on, access will be controlled," the house manager confirmed.
The occupiers, who had occupied 11 of the 13 apartments of the building - the rest were inhabited - took the entire electrical system and part of the water supply. In addition, they had painted the walls and left all kinds of garbage, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
In the three lower floors huge parties were celebrated, which lasted up to two days and drove the tenants to despair.
Next to the building is a discotheque, Balmes 51, which also carried damage from it.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that her business had fallen by 80% since the beginning of the occupation of the house.
The owner of the discotheque pointed out that the occupiers made her unfair competition, because they sold the drinks for three euros, while they cost 10 euros in the discotheque.
In addition, the owner of the recreation room had been reported by the neighbors for rest disturbance, while according to her, the noise did not come from the visitors of the disco, but from the occupiers of the house and especially from the guests of the parties organized there, and which, according to the statements of the angry neighbors in recent weeks, have become longer and longer.
The head of the discotheque stated that the harassment was so great that she agreed with the owner of the building not to have to pay rent for the last nine months.
The Guardia Urbana (city police) also confirmed that it has received more complaints from neighbors in recent weeks.
The chairman of the PP (Partido Popular - People's Party) in the city council of Barcelona, Alberto Fern<0xC3><0xA1>ndez D<0xC3><0xAD>az, had last week demanded to immediately clear the building and get control of the problems of civil coexistence and the downfall of the district.
He explained that before the summer only one floor of the building had been occupied, but that in recent months the occupants had entered all the floors of the building and almost all the apartments. In some there had even been thefts.
In this sense, he added that "it is necessary to put an end to impunity and to intervene against the asocial actions in the building."
Yesterday, another building in the Nou Barris district was cleared by the Catalan police.
At 3:30 p.m., police approached Montral Street No. 35 after receiving a call from a neighbor who had watched four people enter the building.
The four were immediately arrested.
Park or mountain?
Apart from the disputes over the fees, the architects agree to the tender.
The urban tender for the 16 gates opens the debate on the importance of Collserola in Barcelona.
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-disappeared Corporaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this administration published its derogatory paper on the promotion of Collserola.
The brochure described the mountain as a huge park in Barcelona city.
It was even compared in numbers to New York’s Central Park.
With the demise of the CMB in 1987, the park became again the upper limit of Barcelona in the eyes of many, because the capital of Catalonia is one of the few that does not spread in a north-south direction, but upwards (mountains) and downwards (seas).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park plays with this idea.
As an example, now not Central Park, but Yellowstone with wild boars in the role of the yogi bear.
So far, when the city in September issued a giant tender, consisting of 16 competitions, for further access doors to Collserola.
Undoubtedly, a gate points to the concept of a park.
Either this is the case, or someone is planning to set goals on the land.
The question arises of itself: Collserola, park or mountain?
The call for proposals is not only from an organizational point of view, but also in terms of a reflection on the city the topic of discussion in the mouth of all architects from Barcelona.
It is almost a recurring theme that two members of this old-fashioned caste who meet in the elevator can resort to.
And it is precisely this fact that provides the fabric for one of the rare matches between what three architects from Barcelona think about it, and some university professors who have applied for the project.
Miguel Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, Daniel Modol and Marta Bayona: The tender is appropriate.
For Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n, "it is necessary" to talk about the "front on the mountains" after the attack on the coast, as far as the discourse of Ildefons Cerda, which is over the green apples, has not been held.
"One should assume that Barcelona's largest park is the beach.
Among other things, because it is easily accessible.
Collserola is more complex," says the architect, for whom the title "Gates of Collserola" contains a "lexical trap": one may not imagine it "as access to a park, but as a limitation of areas on which to act."
Modol, like Rold<0xC3><0xA1>n and Bayona with urban planning experience, sees the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" that carries "some dangers".
Dangers due to the "uncertainty that comes with the design of a public space today" according to the experiences of the 1980s, which had their "swan song" in the forum area.
The first fear is one’s own limitation on what may be built.
“To limit something always means to set the next step,” i.e., to exceed it.
"You have to think about new urban planning instruments, because the current [referring to the General Metropolitano Plan (PGM) ] can lead to a real disaster."
Modol, who sticks closer to the question, thinks simplified, the side of Collserola that goes towards Vallesana, "can be understood as a park that does not go towards Barcelona", and for purely topographical reasons.
Modol recalls that there is already a study by the Patronat de Collserola, which should not "stumble on deaf ears", although he is grateful to the city administration for giving his body the opportunity to participate in this project "from the first moment".
In addition, he notes that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the guideline that allows the architects to participate in the debate, although he expresses his "doubts" about whether this technical profile should guide the multidisciplinary teams created ("just the right thing," he says).
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question in the title of this article is complex, as the tender terms lack a global view of Collserola: "There were 16 cross-sectional competitions," he says, "on the mountain-sea axis. But there is no longitudinal perspective that views the area as a whole."
At least in his case, this has led to him taking part in the 16 competitions.
Otherwise, the program and the definition of a project for a gate would collide with that of the architect of the gate next to it.
In his opinion, the city should absolutely guarantee that the strip is equipped directly above the Ronda de Dalt in its entire length, which creates a soft transition between the city and green zones.
