MSS Announces Research Protocol to Find the Gene for Obesity
The Social Insurance Institution of Mexico is leading a research project to find the gene for obesity in children and adolescents, which is supported by specialists of the IPN.
The Instituto Mexicano del Seguro Social - IMSS (Social Insurance Institution of Mexico) announced that it is leading a research project to discover the gene for obesity in children and adolescents under the title "Genetics of obesity in childhood and youth", with which the genetic markers associated with obesity are to be found.
Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Unidad de Investigaci<0xC3><0xB3>n Médica en Bioqu<0xC3><0xAD>mica (Department of Medical Research, Biochemistry) at the Hospital de Especialidades del Centro Médico Nacional Siglo XXI, explained that an interdisciplinary team consisting of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was formed.
This team is supported by specialists and students of the postgraduate program at the Instituto Nacional de Salud P<0xC3><0xBA>blica (INSP) and the Centro de Investigaci<0xC3><0xB3>n y de Estudios Avanzados (Cinvestav) of the Instituto Politécnico Nacional (IPN).
The population is invited to participate in the study. Interested parties can come to the IMSS sports grounds in the Valley of Mexico, where tests with children and adolescents are carried out every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He emphasized that the investigation began on the Cuauhtémoc sports field (in the west of the state of Mexico) and has been continued since October 8 on the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt sports field (in the east of the state of Mexico).
When the target of 500 to 600 subjects is reached, the study will be continued on the Independencia sports field (in the south of the capital district) and completed on the Morelos sports field (in the north of the capital district).
He explained that the aim of the study was to learn about the factors and the role of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify risk factors of Mexican children and adolescents for the prevention of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the World Diabetes Day, he stated that it is intended that three thousand children and adolescents between the ages of six and 14 should complete dietary questionnaires with the consent and supervision of their parents.
They will also be asked questions about their physical activity and their family history of illness in order to control risk factors that could result in diabetes or kidney failure.
He also concluded that on the aforementioned Saturdays, the subjects measured (weight, size, waist circumference), their blood pressure was controlled and blood values such as glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin and genetic factors (an attempt to identify genes related to obesity in childhood) would be determined.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez stressed that this study would be carried out on the occasion of the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain of young people.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys showed that in just under six years, the proportion of obese boys increased by 77 percent and that of girls with obesity by 47 percent, and obesity also increased dramatically," the IMSS specialist emphasized.
He stated that the search for genetic markers was justified because the genetic history of the people of Mexico differed from that of other peoples.
He stated that an average Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, which is reflected in the genes associated with diabetes and obesity.
Quite generally, he explained, the genetics of obesity is expressed in the inability to burn the excess energy (calories) taken from us, so that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the study participants would be a comprehensive study of the children, which would determine whether they exhibited a degree of overweight or obesity.
It would even investigate the occurrence of dark skin folds in the neck and inner arm (acanthosis), which indicate the likelihood of metabolic disorders and diabetes in the pre-stage.
All information would be treated confidentially and communicated to the parents in writing by the doctors. The doctors will explain to the parents all the measurement results and suggest lifestyle changes that are appropriate for the prevention of diseases.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three basic factors that are responsible for overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: lack of movement, that is, lack of movement in everyday life, spending most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transportation, instead of walking short distances.
The high calorie intake, that is, an increased consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) together with a high fat and protein intake as well as the genetics to be analyzed in this research project.
Asphalt from UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University UNAM develops polymer-modified asphalts to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
Respecting the signs coming out of the road pavement, it would not be necessary to repair nearly 200,000 bump holes if the rainy season in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the Valley of Mexico) breaks out, said Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry, who was putting up so much damage to the pavement at the University of Applied Sciences (FQ).
In his lecture "Stroke holes from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, which, however, exhibits a greater mechanical resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera argued that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of the road surface and thus avoid the appearance of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of petroleum - is a hydrocarbon compound, some of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together they give the road surface its characteristic tough elastic behavior.
Tightening elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C. it is very tightly liquid and at 50° C. it is almost solid, while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of the asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City have a mostly flexible road surface, consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Between the top layers lies an abrasion layer of asphalt, consisting of small, asphalt-soaked and then hardened stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on it and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he concluded, "a final layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e., sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and it needs to produce friction.
This road surface receives and distributes most of the forces, the support layer also needs a suitable thickness and the material from which it is made must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other important factors to take into account, especially the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water enters the layer and only enters difficult again. This causes softening of all layers of the road surface and, as a result, the appearance of impact holes.
When a percussion hole is created, he said, "the cover layer will be removed at first, while the wear layer will only be affected after that. But the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that should be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the appearance of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that to avoid frequent impact holes these rules
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there was still a lot of research to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the perforations could be repaired easily and without the application of high temperatures.
