This was the work of the doctor who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who identified "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials plays a key role.
On November 4, a lophoscopist of the Cali State Prosecutor’s Office’s Investigation Unit (CTI) went in as the man who confirmed the identity of the leader of the FARC (Fuerzas Armadas Revolucionarias de Colombia – Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia) by comparing the fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists in the CTI department, this week Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez had preparedness service, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been involved in criminal investigations for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in communities of Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where he often had to go to the jungle for five days to reach the place where the bodies he was supposed to identify were located.
In 2000 he moved to Valle over and after completing the required courses he specialized in lophoscopy, that is, the examination of the skin that is exposed to friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
In the week of the operation against the so-called Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was told to pack clothes for at least three days.
Something big was waiting for him.
Friday night he flew in a helicopter from Palmira to Cauca.
He knew that he should identify two bodies, and that there was a suspicion that one of them might be that of the man who had led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he should take the ten-finger imprint of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz (his real name).
However, when he reached the place where the body was found with the test, he could not identify him because of his physical appearance, because this was not in the least similar to the images he had seen in the mass media.
He had no beard, was dressed like a farmer in the area, did not wear glasses and was very much thinner.
Fingerprints don’t lie.
Armed with a magnifying glass, ink, a planting cell and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those on the imprint sheet.
He said it was Alfonso Cano.
The same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was responsible for informing the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n, that he was in fact the head of the FARC.
Searching for clues
For a dactyloscopic from the Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n in Cali, the appreciation that President Juan Manuel Santos Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez gave at a press conference on the use of "Cano" was very important.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science with no error rate, which can be a key factor in the resolution of a crime.
Lophoscopists not only identify bodies, they also support investigations into murder and robbery cases and confirm the identity of the arrested persons.
At the time of their arrest, many criminals present false ID documents or they do not have any.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher told us that he had to tear a piece of wall out of a house in the event of a theft, because the thief had supported himself with his hand right here when he pulled out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"Walls are difficult because their surfaces are unsuitable for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to take the whole hand print and identify the offender who participated in several thefts," he recalled.
With the help of fingerprints, murder suspects can also be relieved or charged.
Recently, a dead man was found surrounded by bottles of candy.
In the investigation, it was suspected that a family member might be suspicious, and in fact, a fingerprint on the bottle matched.
Although this does not guarantee that it is the murderer, it is still associated with the place where the crime was committed.
A CTI daktyloscopist explained that "the fingerprints would be taken from the object with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a planting cell or band is used to carry them.
Afterwards, the prints are sent to Asif, the criminal database, or to the People's Office.
“The problem is that there are still many Colombians without IDs,” the CTI expert said.
He said not everything was as it would be in the TV series SCI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that you touch is a fingerprint.
But it can still be used if a corresponding comparison is made.
