Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the free-fall spiral from the beginning of March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that led to a nuclear crisis, and the worst disaster Japan had experienced since World War II.
The government’s first estimates in Tokyo estimated the property damage at $300,000, a blow that seems to be weakening despite the difficult global economic situation.
After three quarters of cases, the data on gross domestic product from July to September finally served to complete this chapter: GDP grew by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at the rate calculated for the year.
The value measured in the second quarter - in Japan, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also means the fastest growth since the period from January to March 2010.
