Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, it is certainly the energy policy.
Availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power as well as the competitiveness of companies.
It is reasonable to hold an election meeting to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it probes the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, a huge proportion of the world’s population should not have to do without a vital element.
At the same time, we must alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity sustainably, without forgetting the imperative to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to combat climate irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
As a result, Germany remains isolated in its decision to abstain from nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source, nor in Switzerland, which just now intends to build only the last generation nuclear power plants.
The UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name just a few, continue to pursue their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, has decided to return to Fukushima to its park by re-opening the Three Mile Island plant, which was shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even if the German model, which is oriented towards renewable energy sources, is sometimes set as a model, the reality, however, contradicts the discourse.
The election in Berlin will take the form of an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence on imported gas, in particular from Russia, and an increase in CO2 emissions from gas and coal-fired power plants.
All of these unpleasant effects will become noticeable within a few months.
The case of Denmark provides an occasion for reflection.
On the one hand, Denmark is the European leader in terms of wind energy, from which it receives 30% of its electricity, on the other hand, the country is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, alternately used with wind energy; on the basis of this, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the stability of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than our French households.
As the energy price plays a key role in competitiveness in the globalised economy as well as a guarantee of stability for industry on a national level, French companies have an advantage due to the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore entail a sharp increase in the price of energy, which would make the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power an illusion.
Surveys have shown that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are willing to pay just as little as they show resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let’s face it, our country’s energy policy has made it possible to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a large number of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises to the international markets and makes them creators of countless jobs.
Should France decide to step down from nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion in investment goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would hire an EPR designed to work for sixty years if its producer’s downfall is pre-programmed?
In order to solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that there is as little a means of generating electricity as there is a devil’s work.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy demonstrate the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a safety authority that performs uncompromising and transparent checks on existing plants such as the construction site in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just obsessed with the idea of safety.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three major disruptions.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, has entered under normal operating conditions, so it went without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was provoked by reactor construction as well as innumerable human failure.
At Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude, which caused the deaths of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident just as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as the cooperation of the security authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR presents a design that allows it to be resistant to such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable among the electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF, leaving them free to tear up the leadership position in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is inevitable and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers dominate a debate that also determines our country’s economic, social and financial situation.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy conducted under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overloading of police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France had itself titled.
Recently, the harassment of foreign students by the government had shaped the weekly shows, the interior minister had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "needed no talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy has rarely been analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus between the right and the left on this issue.
From the right side, the tone was struck by Jacques Chirac, who had declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people, including over 2 million migrant workers, should not be a problem for a country", from the left side by Michel Rocard, who had explained in 1990 that France "could not absorb all the poverty of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
The fear of invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared in 2005 by both right and left.
From both camps, immigrants were perceived as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that one is willing to admit to the immigrants.
Francois Hollande, in his programme, confines himself to banalities that indicate that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This notion of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may affect the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As the economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present us in a recently published work on economics, which summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a positive one among the specialists on the topic of economics.
Reducing immigration would deter growth and damage the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to replace local workers, in particular those with lower qualifications, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that immigrants are in fact much more complementary than domestic wage earners, as they focus heavily on occupations in sectors that are technically job-free.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic wage workers, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not equal to the job offer.
Positive Salary Effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anesthesiologists, this complementarity between locals and migrants has a positive effect on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
In this way, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in immigrant flooding would result in a long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity introduced by immigrants is conducive to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of immigrant citizens among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to social systems, on average about 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 brings a net contribution (income minus expenses) of around 150,000 euros to the public budget on average over his lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to bring about the lack of intersections "with the teeth" in the beginning of his term of office.
However, these said teeth, which should deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, now it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also a sensitive asset.
The European continent should be able to remember for itself who, according to its invention in Athens more than two thousand years ago, had let the entire 20th century over the tragedies of the First World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Francos in Spain, Salazars in Portugal and the Colonel in Greece.
Some had thought it sufficient to exercise the right to vote, in the most direct way possible, to see democracy conquer its enemies once and for all.
It has been known since Napoleon "the little one" that it was a feature of the mental attitude.
The general right to vote, which is the necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition for this and can just as well become the "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot expressed at the time.
No, democracy requires far more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social community spirit, jurisprudence.
The crisis in Europe in which we find ourselves is an economic crisis, but it is also a very serious and, first of all, a political and democratic crisis.
The change of mind of the Greek True False Referendum would have had a twofold revealing character in this respect: one of the necessity of a powerful return of politics, but on the other hand also of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its inadequacy.
This ambivalence should be considered outdated.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and that the Republican soldiers, or at least most of them, are no longer aiming in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain in order to push for a success of the national referendum, which was organized according to the needs and in the wrong order.
A free pass for the European sole ruler or a leap with one eye to the void of nationalist retreat: a great choice for the citizen!
No, we want Hackebeil, but a collective task, rightly, enlightened and steady, an election and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - you no longer know where to end the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is prevailing in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is bowing to the dictation of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated at the international level.
One is concerned about the transfer of sovereignty towards Europe - it is the whole of Europe that is gradually losing its sovereignty, and thus every single one of the nations attached to it.
The urgency is to give the leadership of the European project back to the sovereignty of the people.
Because it is up to the whole whether Europeans can reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and start a future through investment.
The exit from the crisis is conditional on decisions at European level that cannot be made without total democratic legitimacy, without certainly leading to our ruin.
After this proposal was fought over by Jacques Delors and the Socialists for a long time, today everyone urges the European economic leadership to do so.
Agreed.
But to imagine this without political integration and a stronger democracy - as it suggests to citizens - would be a new folly and another dead end.
We need to take on a new stage of European integration.
In order to create a republic in France, it was necessary to "create" Republicans.
The revolution of interests alone could not do enough here.
This instruction will remain valid.
We need to create a better integrated Europe at the economic level.
This can only be achieved by creating a more politically democratic Europe, a truly European people's sovereignty.
We need Europeans to create Europe.
"Contactless" chip cards become a common good
The world trade fair for chip cards opens its doors on Tuesday in Villepinte near Paris in an optimistic attitude.
