Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the seabed of the Baltic Sea and connects Western Europe directly to Russia, has been put into operation.
It is expected to supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with brilliance and glory.
More than 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly under sea level, on the Baltic coast last Tuesday under orchestral sound and at a tasty buffet.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have symbolically turned the control of the valve, which transports Russian gas to the Western European network.
The new gas long-distance line will deliver 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas per year through a first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern to Western Europe.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - is expected to be completed by the end of 2012.
And the possibility of building a third line on the same route is already being pointed out.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building seems like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will allow direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any route through third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on the land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing some of their power: for them, it is now becoming more difficult to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most strongly engaged in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the Nord Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in conjunction with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the purpose of the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically highly sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply by supporting this Russian project.
However, this is at the expense of de-empowering European energy, as the project has struck a rift between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has completed its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and tend to their gas reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the large gas contracts are also important from the political and economic side.
All this explains the broad smile of the Gazprom managers, who are numerous in Lubmin, regarding the gas supply.
The construction of this gas transmission line is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater line is made of steel with concrete cladding, which is intended to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, in about 200 m depth.
During its construction, minefields dating from the Second World War had to be diverted.
"About a hundred mines had to be removed or destroyed cautiously," Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream, said.
In addition, intensified measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, as heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted by anything along the entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers distanced themselves from it, as the Swedes had little interest in seeing a Russian state-owned company settle permanently at the level of their coasts.
"In the event of an accident, we will close the gas passage in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In the case of a leak, the gas in the gas transmission line thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers, as the weld seams were estimated to have a resistance of one leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas transmission line is ensured by both an underwater robot, which is controlled for external observation purposes by a seagoing vessel, and by a device circulating inside the gas transmission line.
It has the shape of a cigar, mi<0xCE><0xB2>t one meter in diameter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of movement through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal when it arrives.
The gas transmission line was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo even the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the entry point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
However, management remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF (at 15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gas Union and the French company group GDF Suez (at 9% each) are affiliated here.
These five companies have formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas transmission line.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company the entire capacity of its gas transport, namely on a renewable twenty-year contract.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the real transport gas volume falls out,” said Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas transmission line was secured to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should amount to 7.4 billion euros for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
However, the minority shareholders are hesitant to recover their expenses, as Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline is located on a sandy, pine forested stretch of coastline at Lubmin from the Baltic Sea.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas outlets.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas transmission lines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with one million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
