Moleskine, a brand notebook.
Created by an Italian company about fifteen years ago, Moleskine now wants to give writing a new style.
It has a flair of adventure, hours spent in candlelight writing.
Moleskine’s notebook is easily recognizable, with its black, rectangular envelope, its rubber band, the egg-shell-colored sides, as ageed over time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as it is known today was created in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, which is based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a distinguished design notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then specialist consultant of the company, is responsible for the market launch of the new product.
The notebook was inspired by an old-fashioned production technique called Mole Skin, which refers to a cotton varnish used, for example, for covers of upholstered benches.
This type of notebook was in high demand among writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and almost forgotten object that was considered to be an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," explains Maria Sebregondi, now brand manager at Modo Modo.
Success comes.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% and established with a sales of 12.7 million units.
This is far from the usual production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to create a phantom image of the buyers, as the notebook delights businessmen as well as students and professionals alike.
Moleskine has the image of cosmopolitan, cultured and open-minded customers.
The small Italian company, which initially had 12 employees, now employs over 100 people and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
The company sells its notebooks in bookstores, on internet portals such as Fnac, in small boutiques in the city centers and understands how to enforce its identity.
“We have followed the spirit of time and its new writing needs, which persist despite the booming e-mails,” said Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural trait is accompanied by the development of the company Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition called "Detour", in which architects and artists exhibited their own notebooks.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, the company also launched a leopard print envelope.
Moleskine benefited from its success and this cultural time spirit and knew how to diversify its products: bags, calendars, fillers, computer cases... The brand has the full range of articles.
In the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today’s Syntegra Capital, thus opening a new chapter in Moleskine’s history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a targeted public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is always twice as high as the average: 19% compared to 9% of the total population.
Disappointing?
"No," said <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, director-general of the Adapt association, which organizes the "Work Week for the Disabled."
"The progress achieved in 15 years is considerable."
"The unemployment rate at that time was not double, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still a great deal to be done."
However, it must be said that there are still many obstacles for disabled unemployed people before they get a job.
It is more common for the elderly: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% of them do not have a diploma and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with higher education degrees.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% among the disabled compared to 38% on average.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to re-enter the workforce and that make up the "core of the problem", says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the actual brakes.
The unspoken remains, the attitudes that are certainly developing, but are still slowly developing.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for the magazine La Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a weak level of knowledge about disabled people", which is "overrepresented" by people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually under-represented".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled workers set out in a 1987 law.
These last-mentioned figures from 2008 refer to a quotient of 2.6%.
“We are now at around 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization tasked with collecting contributions from companies that violated this law.
Evidence: The number of "fees payable" establishments decreased from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros) and the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created strong pressure on companies," said Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real insight, especially among the large groups of companies."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of workplaces between 20 and 49 employees employ people with disabilities, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
